  "recommendedActions": "A. Validate the alert.\n1. Locate and inspect the process tree to identify the installed software, the parent process, the account used to launch them, and the command associated with the alert.\n2. Determine whether the communication source is internal or external to the organization. \n3. Verify if the identified activity is expected by contacting the server owner.\n4. Look for any post-exploitation alerts or suspicious activities in the device timeline on the server around or after the time of this alert.\n5. Submit relevant files for deep analysis and review file behaviors.\n\nB. Investigate threat scope and impact\n1. \u00a0Investigate the source and target devices for additional related alerts and activities.\u00a0Find\u00a0out\u00a0whether\u00a0they\u00a0are\u00a0part\u00a0of\u00a0a\u00a0wider\u00a0incident. Use the incident page as guide for the rest of your investigation. Use the alert page, device timeline, and incident graph to investigate related activities.\n2.  Identify unexpected processes, check suspicious files for prevalence, location and digital signature. Identify communications to suspect network addresses and domains. Check network connections initiated by the suspicious process (for example, unusual external IPs or domains). Check recent downloads for any suspicious files.\n3. Pivot on any evidence entities to determine the full scope of the threat and find any additional impacted devices and other assets. Use the entity page Observed in org tab or Advanced Hunting to search for other occurrences of these indicators across the organization.\n\nC. Contain and mitigate the threat.\n1. Isolate any affected accounts or devices, then reset passwords or decommission compromised accounts, stop suspicious processes, and block\u00a0communication\u00a0to\u00a0suspect\u00a0network\u00a0addresses\u00a0and\u00a0domains.\n2. Install security updates. Do a full scan and quarantine malicious files.\n3. Clean up or reinstall affected devices to remove malicious components and return them to a clean state. \n4. Add all identified threat indicators to block lists using the Indicators page.\n\nD. Contact your incident response team, or contact Microsoft support for investigation and remediation services.\n\n",
